06649nam a22008175i 9781478012092DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780120927 a10.1515/97814780120922doi  a(DE-B1597)553723  a(OCoLC)1141023254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a342.730822300aPaper Trails :bMigrants, Documents, and Legal Insecurity /ced. by Josiah Heyman, Sarah B. Horton. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Insecurities : 1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Paper Trails: Migrants, Bureaucratic Inscription, and Legal Recognition -- tPART I. FOUNDATIONS: CONTROLLING SPACE AND TIME -- t1. The “People Out of Place”: State Limits on Free Mobility and the Making of Im(migrants) -- t2. And About Time Too . . . : Migration, Documentation, and Temporalities -- t3. Documenting Membership: The Divergent Politics of Migrant Driver’s Licenses in New Mexico and Arizona -- tPART II. DOCUMENTS AS SECURITY, DOCUMENTS AS VISIBILITY -- t4. Documented as Unauthorized -- t5. Opportunities and Double Binds: Legal Craft in an Era of Uncertainty -- t6. Document Overseers, Enhanced Enforcement, and Racialized Local Contexts: Experiences of Latino/a Immigrants in Phoenix, Arizona -- tPART III. RESISTANCE AND REFUSALS -- t7. Knowing Your Rights in Trump’s America: Paper Trails of Migrant Community Empowerment -- t8. Strategies of Documentation among Kichwa Transnational Migrants -- tConclusion. Documents as Power -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the globe, states have long aimed to control the movement of people, identify their citizens, and restrict noncitizens' rights through official identification documents. Although states are now less likely to grant permanent legal status, they are increasingly issuing new temporary and provisional legal statuses to migrants. Meanwhile, the need for migrants to apply for frequent renewals subjects them to more intensive state surveillance. The contributors to Paper Trails examine how these new developments change migrants' relationship to state, local, and foreign bureaucracies. The contributors analyze, among other toics, immigration policies in the United Kingdom, the issuing of driver's licenses in Arizona and New Mexico, the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, and community know-your-rights campaigns. By demonstrating how migrants are inscribed into official bureaucratic systems through the issuance of identification documents, the contributors open up new ways to understand how states exert their power and how migrants must navigate new systems of governance.Contributors. Bridget Anderson, Deborah A. Boehm, Susan Bibler Coutin, Ruth Gomberg-Muñoz, Sarah B. Horton, Josiah Heyman, Cecilia Menjívar, Juan Thomas Ordóñez, Doris Marie Provine, Nandita Sharma, Monica Varsanyi  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmigration and immigration lawzGreat Britain. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aIdentification cardsxLaw and legislationzGreat Britain. 0aIdentification cardsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  atemporary worker status.1 aAnderson, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoehm, Deborah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoutin, Susan Bibler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomberg-Muñoz, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyman, Josiah, econtributor.